00:02:33.020 --> 00:02:36.910
Talk a little bit about your
experience as a teacher there.

00:02:36.910 --> 00:02:40.030
And then I want to show some
slides of the new media center.

00:02:40.030 --> 00:02:42.150
But first kind of
tee it up with your

00:02:42.150 --> 00:02:44.830
experiences as a teacher at Palo
Alto, how things have changed

00:02:44.830 --> 00:02:45.872
over those last 30 years.

00:02:45.872 --> 00:02:48.455
ESTHER WOJCICKI: OK, so when I
first to Palo Alto High School,

00:02:48.455 --> 00:02:50.090
there was one small
class of students.

00:02:50.090 --> 00:02:52.220
There were 19 kids
in the program.

00:02:52.220 --> 00:02:54.280
We had a typewriter.

00:02:54.280 --> 00:02:56.690
And the kids used to
write their stories up

00:02:56.690 --> 00:02:58.960
and then they would type
them up on a typewriter.

00:02:58.960 --> 00:03:02.190
Then I used to hand out
in class single edge razor

00:03:02.190 --> 00:03:03.740
blades to everybody.

00:03:03.740 --> 00:03:07.480
And they would cut their
story out and then paste it up

00:03:07.480 --> 00:03:09.990
on a paste board with hot wax.

00:03:09.990 --> 00:03:11.080
This was the way it was.

00:03:11.080 --> 00:03:14.440
And then I always got really
mad because I would say,

00:03:14.440 --> 00:03:16.030
it's crooked.

00:03:16.030 --> 00:03:17.990
Got to get this thing straight.

00:03:17.990 --> 00:03:21.270
And after three
years of doing that,

00:03:21.270 --> 00:03:23.470
which was quite a
challenge actually,

00:03:23.470 --> 00:03:24.930
the program had grown.

00:03:24.930 --> 00:03:28.679
And I heard about these
things called computers.

00:03:28.679 --> 00:03:30.720
I was like, oh my god,
something has to be better

00:03:30.720 --> 00:03:31.760
than this typewriter.

00:03:31.760 --> 00:03:35.516
And so that's the
beginning of what

00:03:35.516 --> 00:03:36.640
happened with the computer.

00:03:36.640 --> 00:03:40.720
I actually discovered a Mac
in Los Altos in a small store

00:03:40.720 --> 00:03:43.591
and I applied for a grant,
the State of California,

00:03:43.591 --> 00:03:45.340
and they told me, oh,
you'll never get it.

00:03:45.340 --> 00:03:49.350
You have no idea how
to use this device.

00:03:49.350 --> 00:03:50.250
And I agreed.

00:03:50.250 --> 00:03:51.910
I didn't have any idea.

00:03:51.910 --> 00:03:54.350
But, gutsy, I applied anyway.

00:03:54.350 --> 00:03:57.400
And somehow or other the
State got-- I don't know.

00:03:57.400 --> 00:04:00.266
Somebody made a mistake
and sent them to me.

00:04:00.266 --> 00:04:03.740
And I got seven of them
and I didn't really

00:04:03.740 --> 00:04:05.160
know how to use them at all.

00:04:05.160 --> 00:04:08.360
And so then they were
in the back of the room,

00:04:08.360 --> 00:04:10.210
all boxed nicely.

00:04:10.210 --> 00:04:12.090
And I had to confess
to my students

00:04:12.090 --> 00:04:14.240
that I had no clue
what I was doing.

00:04:14.240 --> 00:04:15.930
And actually that
was the beginning

00:04:15.930 --> 00:04:18.079
of my collaborative
teaching method,

00:04:18.079 --> 00:04:21.860
because all my students got
super excited about this.

00:04:21.860 --> 00:04:25.910
They showed up after school,
evening, weekends and we

00:04:25.910 --> 00:04:28.650
figured out how to
work them together.

00:04:28.650 --> 00:04:30.740
I never even knew what
the word network was,

00:04:30.740 --> 00:04:32.970
but they showed me how to do it.

00:04:32.970 --> 00:04:34.350
We did it all together.

00:04:34.350 --> 00:04:37.090
So then for 30
years-- I probably

00:04:37.090 --> 00:04:39.110
shouldn't give too
much detail on this.

00:04:39.110 --> 00:04:43.559
For 30 years I
was in a portable.

00:04:43.559 --> 00:04:44.350
JAMIE CASAP: Right.

00:04:44.350 --> 00:04:45.830
I've been in that
portable with you.

00:04:45.830 --> 00:04:46.090
I've visited.

00:04:46.090 --> 00:04:46.830
ESTHER WOJCICKI: I know, a
portable, otherwise known

00:04:46.830 --> 00:04:50.090
as a trailer, what was supposed
to be a temporary building.

00:04:50.090 --> 00:04:51.960
And then the program
kept growing.

00:04:51.960 --> 00:04:54.210
Everybody was like, what
is she doing in that class,

00:04:54.210 --> 00:04:56.560
giving out pizza or something?

00:04:56.560 --> 00:05:02.270
And actually the truth is,
I was giving out some pizza.

00:05:02.270 --> 00:05:05.290
But there was more
to it than that.

00:05:05.290 --> 00:05:07.270
So it grew and grew and
grew and pretty soon I

00:05:07.270 --> 00:05:09.402
was in multiple portables
at the same time.

00:05:09.402 --> 00:05:10.860
Kind of interesting
that the school

00:05:10.860 --> 00:05:13.830
thought that I could
supervise multiple classrooms

00:05:13.830 --> 00:05:15.490
at the same time
from one location.

00:05:15.490 --> 00:05:16.772
JAMIE CASAP: How many
students are we talking about

00:05:16.772 --> 00:05:17.410
at this point here?

00:05:17.410 --> 00:05:19.118
ESTHER WOJCICKI: Oh,
at this point, well,

00:05:19.118 --> 00:05:20.700
so it started with, I said, 19.

00:05:20.700 --> 00:05:23.690
At that point I had
80 in one class.

00:05:23.690 --> 00:05:25.894
So it was a ratio of one to 80.

00:05:25.894 --> 00:05:27.560
So it was a little
difficult to control.

00:05:27.560 --> 00:05:29.476
And not only that, they're
all over the place.

00:05:29.476 --> 00:05:32.880
And my method of control
was very different

00:05:32.880 --> 00:05:34.520
than other people's
method of control.

00:05:34.520 --> 00:05:37.020
My method was, you're
going to be doing it.

00:05:37.020 --> 00:05:40.940
I'll give you the tools and
now you take over and do it.

00:05:40.940 --> 00:05:45.960
And so that's what enabled
me to have all these students

00:05:45.960 --> 00:05:47.340
with just one teacher.

00:05:47.340 --> 00:05:48.940
And actually the
interesting thing

00:05:48.940 --> 00:05:52.890
is like, that freedom
and responsibility

00:05:52.890 --> 00:05:56.289
is what attracted all
those kids to my program.

00:05:56.289 --> 00:05:57.830
Everybody really
thought it was food,

00:05:57.830 --> 00:05:59.644
but really it was freedom.

00:05:59.644 --> 00:06:01.060
JAMIE CASAP: It's
food too, right?

00:06:01.060 --> 00:06:02.770
ESTHER WOJCICKI: Well, food
and, yeah, that's true.

00:06:02.770 --> 00:06:04.350
You did have the
food when you came.

00:06:04.350 --> 00:06:05.940
JAMIE CASAP: It was good pizza.

00:06:05.940 --> 00:06:09.120
So the media center opened.

00:06:09.120 --> 00:06:11.950
ESTHER WOJCICKI: Oh yeah,
so then-- So fast forward

00:06:11.950 --> 00:06:13.870
30 years, and the
school district

00:06:13.870 --> 00:06:16.770
built this incredible
building for me,

00:06:16.770 --> 00:06:22.920
25,000 square foot Media Arts
Center, Palo Alto High School.

00:06:22.920 --> 00:06:24.710
It really is shocking.

00:06:24.710 --> 00:06:27.150
Like I said, I went
from this trailer,

00:06:27.150 --> 00:06:28.830
where actually the
roof was leaking

00:06:28.830 --> 00:06:31.371
and a few other things like the
air conditioning didn't work,

00:06:31.371 --> 00:06:33.810
into this thing which I
would consider a palace.

00:06:33.810 --> 00:06:37.180
And you can see all
the different rooms.

00:06:37.180 --> 00:06:40.590
It's got room for
every single program

00:06:40.590 --> 00:06:43.290
that I created over the years.

00:06:43.290 --> 00:06:44.470
And there's the atrium.

00:06:44.470 --> 00:06:47.030
The reason they made
an atrium that big,

00:06:47.030 --> 00:06:49.792
is because my classes
generally ran 80 kids.

00:06:49.792 --> 00:06:52.250
And the question is, what are
you going to do with 80 kids?

00:06:52.250 --> 00:06:54.700
Well, how about packing
them into this atrium.

00:06:54.700 --> 00:06:57.020
And it turns out
that the kids prefer

00:06:57.020 --> 00:06:59.710
to be-- they really like
to be sandwiched together

00:06:59.710 --> 00:07:01.470
in smaller spaces.

00:07:01.470 --> 00:07:04.580
So now they're all in these--
I have three other rooms.

00:07:04.580 --> 00:07:07.320
And they sort of spread
out in those other rooms.

00:07:07.320 --> 00:07:09.552
Although yesterday, they
were all in the atrium.

00:07:09.552 --> 00:07:10.760
We have a lot of flexibility.

00:07:10.760 --> 00:07:11.190
It's great.

00:07:11.190 --> 00:07:13.690
JAMIE CASAP: And what it has
been your experience with this,

00:07:13.690 --> 00:07:16.640
compared to being in those
trailers that you had before?

00:07:16.640 --> 00:07:19.800
What's been your greatest
highlight from this experience?

00:07:19.800 --> 00:07:21.710
And it's only been
open since when?

00:07:21.710 --> 00:07:22.320
ESTHER WOJCICKI:
About eight months.

00:07:22.320 --> 00:07:22.880
JAMIE CASAP: About eight months.

00:07:22.880 --> 00:07:24.338
ESTHER WOJCICKI:
Since last August.

00:07:24.338 --> 00:07:28.210
So the greatest experience--
I mean, it's just unbelievable

00:07:28.210 --> 00:07:30.140
how excited the students are.

00:07:30.140 --> 00:07:33.360
And one of the main
problems that we have is

00:07:33.360 --> 00:07:35.030
get them to go home.

00:07:35.030 --> 00:07:36.460
Nobody wants to leave.

00:07:36.460 --> 00:07:38.460
As a matter of fact, that
was one of the things,

00:07:38.460 --> 00:07:41.370
it's like, it's 5 o'clock
in the afternoon or six,

00:07:41.370 --> 00:07:43.360
how many kids are
still in the building?

00:07:43.360 --> 00:07:46.040
Can we ask them to go home?

00:07:46.040 --> 00:07:48.950
And they are working
collaboratively,

00:07:48.950 --> 00:07:51.530
so they actually
want to stay there.

00:07:51.530 --> 00:07:55.830
That's just one that you just
had, that one computer lab.

00:07:55.830 --> 00:07:59.130
That's one of three.

00:07:59.130 --> 00:08:04.020
Back in the olden
days, in that portable,

00:08:04.020 --> 00:08:07.100
I had a computer lab that I
had to share with other people.

00:08:07.100 --> 00:08:09.430
Frequently that
computers didn't work.

00:08:09.430 --> 00:08:11.070
And not only that,
I was supposed

00:08:11.070 --> 00:08:13.030
to be in that room and
the computer lab, which

00:08:13.030 --> 00:08:14.821
was, of course, on the
other side of campus

00:08:14.821 --> 00:08:15.632
at the same time.

00:08:15.632 --> 00:08:17.715
JAMIE CASAP: And all your
furniture is all movable

00:08:17.715 --> 00:08:22.000
so you can create collaborative
spaces and teams can

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:24.240
set themselves up in different
corners of the space.

00:08:24.240 --> 00:08:25.560
ESTHER WOJCICKI: You see
those desks right there?

00:08:25.560 --> 00:08:26.560
They move.

00:08:26.560 --> 00:08:29.030
And so kids, I can
say get into a group.

00:08:29.030 --> 00:08:32.039
And they can all like, scoot
into a group in a minute.

00:08:32.039 --> 00:08:34.157
So I don't believe
in desks and rows.

00:08:34.157 --> 00:08:35.740
JAMIE CASAP: Are
they good for racing?

00:08:35.740 --> 00:08:36.490
Can you race them?

00:08:36.490 --> 00:08:39.143
ESTHER WOJCICKI: Well, actually
they have had some races.

00:08:39.143 --> 00:08:41.650
We've had to control
it a little bit.

00:08:41.650 --> 00:08:46.790
But in general, we
don't have rows.

00:08:46.790 --> 00:08:48.820
We have kids working
collaboratively.

00:08:48.820 --> 00:08:51.740
That is a picture of--
that was the grand opening

00:08:51.740 --> 00:08:52.750
for the building.

00:08:52.750 --> 00:08:56.680
It had three really amazing
people, Arianna Huffington,

00:08:56.680 --> 00:08:58.830
and David Kelley
from the d.school.

00:08:58.830 --> 00:09:02.330
And Shelby Coffey from the
Newseum in Washington, DC.

00:09:02.330 --> 00:09:04.970
They had an amazing panel.

00:09:04.970 --> 00:09:08.757
It was great and I'm
sorry we didn't record it,

00:09:08.757 --> 00:09:09.340
unfortunately.

00:09:12.421 --> 00:09:14.670
JAMIE CASAP: So let's talk
a little bit about what you

00:09:14.670 --> 00:09:15.878
do in the Media Center right?

00:09:15.878 --> 00:09:20.420
So in education, I think one
of the reasons why you're

00:09:20.420 --> 00:09:22.180
highlighted in what
you do is because you

00:09:22.180 --> 00:09:25.870
have this unique way of
controlling your kids, which

00:09:25.870 --> 00:09:27.750
is not to control them right?

00:09:27.750 --> 00:09:30.340
So talk a little bit
about what you do.

00:09:30.340 --> 00:09:33.630
We hear a lot in education,
project-based learning,

00:09:33.630 --> 00:09:34.430
blended learning.

00:09:34.430 --> 00:09:37.580
What are these terms, what
do these terminologies mean?

00:09:37.580 --> 00:09:39.750
How do you use this
in the classroom?

00:09:39.750 --> 00:09:40.650
ESTHER WOJCICKI: So
blended learning,

00:09:40.650 --> 00:09:43.108
I don't know how many of you
know what blended learning is,

00:09:43.108 --> 00:09:46.760
but it really is an
opportunity to give students

00:09:46.760 --> 00:09:48.184
more control of their learning.

00:09:48.184 --> 00:09:49.600
So typical classroom--
as a matter

00:09:49.600 --> 00:09:52.810
of fact, 80% of the
classrooms today, the teacher

00:09:52.810 --> 00:09:55.790
still lectures 100% of the time.

00:09:55.790 --> 00:09:58.690
And so the question is,
how effective is that?

00:09:58.690 --> 00:10:00.490
And the answer really
for the most part,

00:10:00.490 --> 00:10:02.680
is it's not very effective.

00:10:02.680 --> 00:10:05.040
People, you know, they
daydream, they do other things.

00:10:05.040 --> 00:10:06.530
It just doesn't really work.

00:10:06.530 --> 00:10:09.030
And people learn by doing.

00:10:09.030 --> 00:10:11.630
Tom Dewey said,
many, many years ago,

00:10:11.630 --> 00:10:14.630
100 years ago to be exact,
that people learn by doing,

00:10:14.630 --> 00:10:17.400
but unfortunately,
education takes a long time

00:10:17.400 --> 00:10:18.720
to figure that out.

00:10:18.720 --> 00:10:24.050
And so what I want my students
do and blended learning is,

00:10:24.050 --> 00:10:28.370
is 50% of the time, they
are working on something

00:10:28.370 --> 00:10:29.710
that's a project-based.

00:10:29.710 --> 00:10:32.190
Actually in my classes
it's more than 50%,

00:10:32.190 --> 00:10:36.220
but for the rest of the
nation, can they somehow

00:10:36.220 --> 00:10:38.930
give students some opportunity
to control their learning?

00:10:38.930 --> 00:10:40.320
That's the key.

00:10:40.320 --> 00:10:43.570
Because the question is even
just here, working at Google,

00:10:43.570 --> 00:10:45.890
how excited would
you be about what

00:10:45.890 --> 00:10:47.980
you're doing if
somebody told you

00:10:47.980 --> 00:10:51.250
what to do 100% of the time?

00:10:51.250 --> 00:10:54.200
Nobody likes to be bossed
around all the time.

00:10:54.200 --> 00:10:55.950
And that's what's
happening unfortunately,

00:10:55.950 --> 00:10:57.130
in a lot of schools.

00:10:57.130 --> 00:10:59.100
JAMIE CASAP: And I
think one of things

00:10:59.100 --> 00:11:02.071
that people get surprised at,
we talk about blended learning,

00:11:02.071 --> 00:11:03.570
we talk about
project0based learning

00:11:03.570 --> 00:11:07.200
as having a product at the
end of your experience.

00:11:07.200 --> 00:11:09.450
And I think a lot of times
when we think about student

00:11:09.450 --> 00:11:12.640
projects, we think about the
volcano with tissue paper

00:11:12.640 --> 00:11:13.160
or whatever.

00:11:13.160 --> 00:11:15.140
But your students are
creating real stuff.

00:11:15.140 --> 00:11:16.890
So I want to highlight
a couple of things,

00:11:16.890 --> 00:11:18.700
if you can talk about
some of the things

00:11:18.700 --> 00:11:20.400
that your students
are actually doing.

00:11:20.400 --> 00:11:24.090
ESTHER WOJCICKI: So if you just
think about the teenage years,

00:11:24.090 --> 00:11:26.047
kids want to be independent.

00:11:26.047 --> 00:11:26.630
Isn't that it?

00:11:26.630 --> 00:11:28.339
Number one, they want
to be independent.

00:11:28.339 --> 00:11:30.380
As a matter of fact, if
they see a parent coming,

00:11:30.380 --> 00:11:31.920
they usually cross the street.

00:11:31.920 --> 00:11:33.000
I don't have any parents.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:36.380
I was born kind of under
a rock or something.

00:11:36.380 --> 00:11:37.440
That's typical.

00:11:37.440 --> 00:11:38.825
Most kids want to
be independent.

00:11:38.825 --> 00:11:41.158
It's not, of course, that
they don't love their parents.

00:11:41.158 --> 00:11:44.060
It's just that it's
a time in life when

00:11:44.060 --> 00:11:45.480
they're seeking independence.

00:11:45.480 --> 00:11:50.040
So I try to build into that by
giving them the independence

00:11:50.040 --> 00:11:51.317
to create these projects.

00:11:51.317 --> 00:11:52.400
And the projects are real.

00:11:52.400 --> 00:11:53.840
So this is "The Campanile."

00:11:53.840 --> 00:11:55.550
It was founded in 1918.

00:11:55.550 --> 00:11:58.160
It's the student newspaper
at Palo Alto High School

00:11:58.160 --> 00:12:01.290
and it runs 28 pages,
three sections,

00:12:01.290 --> 00:12:02.830
comes out every three weeks.

00:12:02.830 --> 00:12:05.990
And it also has a
website and it also

00:12:05.990 --> 00:12:08.449
how has a magazine
that goes with it.

00:12:08.449 --> 00:12:10.490
JAMIE CASAP: And they go
through the same process

00:12:10.490 --> 00:12:13.910
that any news organization will
go through, editorial board,

00:12:13.910 --> 00:12:14.740
editors.

00:12:14.740 --> 00:12:15.906
ESTHER WOJCICKI: Everything.

00:12:15.906 --> 00:12:18.070
Not only that, they
support it themselves.

00:12:18.070 --> 00:12:19.990
So one of the hardest
things for them to do

00:12:19.990 --> 00:12:21.610
is to sell advertising.

00:12:21.610 --> 00:12:22.650
They are terrified.

00:12:22.650 --> 00:12:24.030
It's kind of interesting.

00:12:24.030 --> 00:12:25.500
It's very hard.

00:12:25.500 --> 00:12:27.510
But my idea is,
like I say to them,

00:12:27.510 --> 00:12:29.590
no more Girl Scout Cookies.

00:12:29.590 --> 00:12:31.530
You're no longer these
cute little things.

00:12:31.530 --> 00:12:34.760
You're going to have to give
people value for whatever it

00:12:34.760 --> 00:12:37.180
is they're paying for.

00:12:37.180 --> 00:12:39.450
And you also have to
learn how to do this.

00:12:39.450 --> 00:12:41.240
This is American society.

00:12:41.240 --> 00:12:42.820
And so they do it.

00:12:42.820 --> 00:12:43.900
So the whole thing.

00:12:43.900 --> 00:12:45.120
This is "Verde Magazine."

00:12:45.120 --> 00:12:47.220
I founded that in 2000.

00:12:47.220 --> 00:12:49.220
And this is "C Magazine."

00:12:49.220 --> 00:12:51.370
It comes out with
"The Campanile."

00:12:51.370 --> 00:12:54.547
So they copied it from
"The New York Times."

00:12:54.547 --> 00:12:57.130
As a matter of fact, doesn't it
look like "The New York Times"

00:12:57.130 --> 00:12:59.490
a little bit?

00:12:59.490 --> 00:13:01.420
And it comes out
every three weeks.

00:13:01.420 --> 00:13:04.439
It's 28 pages,
full color glossy.

00:13:04.439 --> 00:13:05.480
JAMIE CASAP: Oops, sorry.

00:13:05.480 --> 00:13:06.521
ESTHER WOJCICKI: Go back.

00:13:06.521 --> 00:13:09.180
So this is daily.

00:13:09.180 --> 00:13:11.760
We broadcast daily
to the school.

00:13:11.760 --> 00:13:13.050
We have closed circuit.

00:13:13.050 --> 00:13:15.640
But it's also online, so
you can see it right away.

00:13:15.640 --> 00:13:17.030
And you can see the archives.

00:13:17.030 --> 00:13:19.630
The parents can see
what they're doing.

00:13:19.630 --> 00:13:24.060
And this was founded in 2007.

00:13:24.060 --> 00:13:26.190
The question was, how to
get all those guys that

00:13:26.190 --> 00:13:27.526
don't want to learn to write?

00:13:27.526 --> 00:13:29.400
Well, how are you going
to get them to write?

00:13:29.400 --> 00:13:31.980
Well, the main thing they want
to do is play sports, right?

00:13:31.980 --> 00:13:34.120
So the question is, what
are they interested in?

00:13:34.120 --> 00:13:35.260
How about sports?

00:13:35.260 --> 00:13:36.810
Let them write about each other.

00:13:36.810 --> 00:13:38.180
And they loved it.

00:13:38.180 --> 00:13:40.430
And so, it's a very
popular program

00:13:40.430 --> 00:13:43.160
and it's a great
magazine and a website.

00:13:43.160 --> 00:13:44.010
This is "The Voice."

00:13:44.010 --> 00:13:48.440
This is a website, it's daily,
updated multiple times a day.

00:13:48.440 --> 00:13:51.844
And they write about whatever
again, that's important.

00:13:51.844 --> 00:13:53.260
So one of the
things we want to do

00:13:53.260 --> 00:13:56.170
is give them the
responsibility to know

00:13:56.170 --> 00:13:58.130
what it is that's
important to write about.

00:13:58.130 --> 00:14:00.260
That is really hard
for most teenagers.

00:14:00.260 --> 00:14:02.580
As a matter of fact, in the
beginning journalism class,

00:14:02.580 --> 00:14:05.350
it takes me about 10
weeks to get them out

00:14:05.350 --> 00:14:07.830
of the mode of
tell me what to do

00:14:07.830 --> 00:14:10.380
to get an A. That's
all they want

00:14:10.380 --> 00:14:12.840
to know, how do I get an A?

00:14:12.840 --> 00:14:15.210
And it's a real
problem, because you

00:14:15.210 --> 00:14:17.800
want to hire people
who actually think

00:14:17.800 --> 00:14:20.270
for themselves, independent,
feel good about it,

00:14:20.270 --> 00:14:21.580
willing to take a risk.

00:14:21.580 --> 00:14:24.290
And you don't get that if
you sit in the classroom

00:14:24.290 --> 00:14:26.919
and told what to do all the
time and worry about your grade.

00:14:26.919 --> 00:14:27.710
JAMIE CASAP: Right.

00:14:27.710 --> 00:14:29.460
And I think it's
important to highlight

00:14:29.460 --> 00:14:31.680
these, because I think
most people would agree,

00:14:31.680 --> 00:14:35.905
seeing these, you would think
that any professional publisher

00:14:35.905 --> 00:14:38.280
were producing these, when in
fact, it's your high school

00:14:38.280 --> 00:14:39.488
students that are doing this.

00:14:39.488 --> 00:14:42.000
And I think that disconnect
between what is project-based

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:44.620
learning and what really
is project-based learning

00:14:44.620 --> 00:14:48.170
is highlighted and
shown with the products

00:14:48.170 --> 00:14:49.780
that your kids are producing.

00:14:49.780 --> 00:14:50.090
ESTHER WOJCICKI: Right.

00:14:50.090 --> 00:14:52.006
They make a difference
in their own community.

00:14:52.006 --> 00:14:55.700
For example, we have a program,
a teacher adviser program,

00:14:55.700 --> 00:14:57.900
where we got rid of
the counseling system.

00:14:57.900 --> 00:15:00.830
And we have-- every teacher
has like, 60 students that they

00:15:00.830 --> 00:15:03.300
act as a counselor-adviser to.

00:15:03.300 --> 00:15:05.910
That came about as a
result of an article

00:15:05.910 --> 00:15:08.430
in "The Campanile" newspaper.

00:15:08.430 --> 00:15:10.460
And so they know
they're empowered.

00:15:10.460 --> 00:15:11.690
It makes a difference.

00:15:11.690 --> 00:15:13.239
And so they're
really interested.

00:15:13.239 --> 00:15:15.780
JAMIE CASAP: And you can't get
rid of your students, can you?

00:15:15.780 --> 00:15:20.430
ESTHER WOJCICKI: So this is
my class size, ratio 1 to 70.

00:15:20.430 --> 00:15:22.480
And so the question
is, do I control them?

00:15:22.480 --> 00:15:24.250
Well, the answer
is, they control

00:15:24.250 --> 00:15:27.340
each other and themselves,
based on the learning

00:15:27.340 --> 00:15:30.050
and based on the
philosophy in the program.

00:15:30.050 --> 00:15:33.840
And I don't have problems
with kids cutting class.

00:15:33.840 --> 00:15:35.530
As I mentioned, my
number one problem

00:15:35.530 --> 00:15:37.770
is, can you please go home?

00:15:37.770 --> 00:15:42.059
And we're happy you're here.

00:15:42.059 --> 00:15:43.600
JAMIE CASAP: But
you want to go home.

00:15:43.600 --> 00:15:44.940
ESTHER WOJCICKI: Yeah,
Mom and Dad miss you.

00:15:44.940 --> 00:15:46.030
JAMIE CASAP: So
you wrote a book.

00:15:46.030 --> 00:15:47.988
I don't know how you
found the time to do this.

00:15:47.988 --> 00:15:50.190
I'm a little jealous
and I'm curious.

00:15:50.190 --> 00:15:52.440
So we'll have more conversation
about how you actually

00:15:52.440 --> 00:15:54.037
had time put all this together.

00:15:54.037 --> 00:15:55.120
But let's talk about this.

00:15:55.120 --> 00:15:57.470
Why did you write a book?

00:15:57.470 --> 00:15:59.160
What's the message in the book?

00:15:59.160 --> 00:16:01.979
What are you trying to
get across with this book?

00:16:01.979 --> 00:16:03.520
ESTHER WOJCICKI: So
I wrote this book

00:16:03.520 --> 00:16:06.920
because I'm trying to spread
this idea of how you can

00:16:06.920 --> 00:16:10.070
do project-based learning
that is not, as you say,

00:16:10.070 --> 00:16:13.650
you know volcanoes and I
don't know missions and things

00:16:13.650 --> 00:16:16.130
like that, you know,
the mission project.

00:16:16.130 --> 00:16:18.970
And because this is real world.

00:16:18.970 --> 00:16:20.060
This makes an impact.

00:16:20.060 --> 00:16:22.670
And so I wanted other
kids around the country

00:16:22.670 --> 00:16:24.700
to have the same opportunity.

00:16:24.700 --> 00:16:29.060
Because our dropout rate in
America today is about 40%.

00:16:29.060 --> 00:16:31.370
And these people then
don't have skills.

00:16:31.370 --> 00:16:33.950
So how can you engage kids?

00:16:33.950 --> 00:16:37.890
They don't have to be like super
smart Palo Alto, wealthy kids.

00:16:37.890 --> 00:16:39.460
They can be any kid.

00:16:39.460 --> 00:16:42.370
I think no matter what
your income level is,

00:16:42.370 --> 00:16:45.350
you want to be trusted,
you want to be respected,

00:16:45.350 --> 00:16:47.520
and you want to be
given some freedom.

00:16:47.520 --> 00:16:49.460
And so that's the goal.

00:16:49.460 --> 00:16:52.547
JAMIE CASAP: Before we get
into some of meat of the-

00:16:52.547 --> 00:16:53.630
ESTHER WOJCICKI: The book?

00:16:53.630 --> 00:16:55.610
JAMIE CASAP: --the
book itself, let's

00:16:55.610 --> 00:16:57.710
talk a little bit about
who wrote your forward

00:16:57.710 --> 00:16:59.360
and how that came about.

00:16:59.360 --> 00:17:01.010
ESTHER WOJCICKI: So
this is my forward.

00:17:01.010 --> 00:17:03.760
It's written by James
Franco, the actor.

00:17:03.760 --> 00:17:05.920
And the reason he
wrote the forward

00:17:05.920 --> 00:17:08.270
is, he was my student
for three years.

00:17:08.270 --> 00:17:09.910
He was in this program.

00:17:09.910 --> 00:17:13.280
His high school was typical
of most student's high school

00:17:13.280 --> 00:17:15.599
experiences, you know,
a little up and down.

00:17:15.599 --> 00:17:19.640
And he bonded with the
program and with me

00:17:19.640 --> 00:17:24.010
and he said that it was the
only place where he really

00:17:24.010 --> 00:17:28.480
learned how important it was to
have a real world experience.

00:17:28.480 --> 00:17:32.350
He wrote, and his articles, he
got feedback on his articles.

00:17:32.350 --> 00:17:34.840
He was kind of shocked
that anybody read them.

00:17:34.840 --> 00:17:38.020
And that he wasn't just
writing for some teacher, who

00:17:38.020 --> 00:17:41.830
would then throws paper
into some circular file.

00:17:41.830 --> 00:17:43.470
He was writing
for the real world

00:17:43.470 --> 00:17:46.160
and it made a huge
impact on his life.

00:17:46.160 --> 00:17:48.260
So he has written the forward.

00:17:48.260 --> 00:17:51.230
He came back for
the grand opening.

00:17:51.230 --> 00:17:55.890
And I invited some people
to come and turns out,

00:17:55.890 --> 00:17:58.180
700 people came to see him.

00:17:58.180 --> 00:18:00.550
It's a little more
than I expected.

00:18:00.550 --> 00:18:03.080
And he was nice
enough to do a selfie

00:18:03.080 --> 00:18:05.594
with every single person.

00:18:05.594 --> 00:18:06.510
I couldn't believe it.

00:18:06.510 --> 00:18:07.968
At the end of that
I thought he was

00:18:07.968 --> 00:18:09.480
going to faint or something.

00:18:09.480 --> 00:18:14.132
But he also made,
he drew or painted--

00:18:14.132 --> 00:18:15.840
I don't know if you
know, he's an artist.

00:18:15.840 --> 00:18:19.840
He painted all these gigantic
paintings for the building.

00:18:19.840 --> 00:18:22.660
So if you come ever-- you're
all welcome, by the way.

00:18:22.660 --> 00:18:24.620
--you'll see paintings
by James Franco.

00:18:24.620 --> 00:18:25.630
And he did a great job.

00:18:25.630 --> 00:18:27.840
JAMIE CASAP: And he
keeps coming back, right?

00:18:27.840 --> 00:18:30.550
There's a bunch of art pieces
that are in the Media Center.

00:18:30.550 --> 00:18:33.537
Like you need to build
a bigger building just

00:18:33.537 --> 00:18:35.370
to keep his art work
that's in there, right?

00:18:35.370 --> 00:18:36.810
ESTHER WOJCICKI: Well, yes.

00:18:36.810 --> 00:18:40.800
He is coming back
often and actually he's

00:18:40.800 --> 00:18:43.400
planning to come back
more often in the fall

00:18:43.400 --> 00:18:46.950
for a special program that will
be announced a later point.

00:18:46.950 --> 00:18:54.480
But I think hats off to him
for spending time and doing

00:18:54.480 --> 00:18:55.510
this for the Palo Alto--

00:18:55.510 --> 00:18:57.301
JAMIE CASAP: And also
highlighting the fact

00:18:57.301 --> 00:18:59.850
that project-based learning
had a huge impact on his life,

00:18:59.850 --> 00:19:03.990
in terms of being able to
see the process of being

00:19:03.990 --> 00:19:06.400
able to get feedback and
collaborating with folks

00:19:06.400 --> 00:19:07.700
and create something.

00:19:07.700 --> 00:19:09.294
I think that had a
huge impact on him.

00:19:09.294 --> 00:19:10.210
ESTHER WOJCICKI: Huge.

00:19:10.210 --> 00:19:12.293
And then also the other
thing that he writes about

00:19:12.293 --> 00:19:17.820
in this forward is how he's
now teaching a lot at UCLA

00:19:17.820 --> 00:19:20.590
and another-- I think it's NYU.

00:19:20.590 --> 00:19:25.160
And he uses this exact
model in his own teaching.

00:19:25.160 --> 00:19:27.900
So that's a part of why
he wrote the forward.

00:19:27.900 --> 00:19:30.370
JAMIE CASAP: So let's talk
about the meat of the book.

00:19:30.370 --> 00:19:31.670
I think I have some slides.

00:19:31.670 --> 00:19:34.780
Oh sorry, I was going to
show you the moon shot slide

00:19:34.780 --> 00:19:36.404
here that you love so much.

00:19:36.404 --> 00:19:37.820
This is you standing
there, right?

00:19:37.820 --> 00:19:39.790
ESTHER WOJCICKI: No.

00:19:39.790 --> 00:19:45.836
This is a statue, fortunately,
donated by my daughter, Anne.

00:19:45.836 --> 00:19:47.860
It arrived the other
day, literally,

00:19:47.860 --> 00:19:48.900
it's only a week there.

00:19:48.900 --> 00:19:52.500
And boy, it's become
number one place to visit.

00:19:52.500 --> 00:19:55.650
And to be honest,
I'm not quite sure

00:19:55.650 --> 00:19:59.060
what she was doing with that
statue and how I got it.

00:19:59.060 --> 00:20:02.835
JAMIE CASAP: Where she get--
the things you can find on eBay.

00:20:02.835 --> 00:20:04.210
ESTHER WOJCICKI:
I have a feeling

00:20:04.210 --> 00:20:05.650
that she had some
kind of a party

00:20:05.650 --> 00:20:06.860
and now I've got the statute.

00:20:09.710 --> 00:20:11.180
I'm not sure.

00:20:11.180 --> 00:20:13.402
But anyway, my students
think it's great

00:20:13.402 --> 00:20:15.610
and everybody's taking their
picture with the statue.

00:20:15.610 --> 00:20:17.650
So whatever, it's great.

00:20:17.650 --> 00:20:19.862
JAMIE CASAP: So one of
the big themes in the book

00:20:19.862 --> 00:20:22.320
and what you're trying to get
across here is about control.

00:20:22.320 --> 00:20:22.630
ESTHER WOJCICKI: Right.

00:20:22.630 --> 00:20:24.810
JAMIE CASAP: And you
highlight-- and I can show you

00:20:24.810 --> 00:20:26.559
some highlights here
about giving students

00:20:26.559 --> 00:20:28.370
some control of their learning.

00:20:28.370 --> 00:20:30.736
Talk a little bit
about what that means.

00:20:30.736 --> 00:20:32.360
You highlighted that
a lot in the book.

00:20:32.360 --> 00:20:33.280
What does that mean?

00:20:33.280 --> 00:20:34.940
ESTHER WOJCICKI: So giving
students some control

00:20:34.940 --> 00:20:35.564
their learning.

00:20:35.564 --> 00:20:38.650
So I think it's really
difficult for teachers

00:20:38.650 --> 00:20:40.040
to give students control.

00:20:40.040 --> 00:20:42.310
Because you come out of
a school of education

00:20:42.310 --> 00:20:44.200
and what happens is,
you've got this book.

00:20:44.200 --> 00:20:46.090
I'm not kidding,
they give you a book,

00:20:46.090 --> 00:20:48.810
how to maintain control
in your classroom.

00:20:48.810 --> 00:20:51.366
Discipline, how to maintain--
yeah, how to achieve this.

00:20:51.366 --> 00:20:53.240
JAMIE CASAP: I was going
to show some slides.

00:20:53.240 --> 00:20:54.448
ESTHER WOJCICKI: There it is.

00:20:54.448 --> 00:20:56.010
Those are just two examples.

00:20:56.010 --> 00:20:57.290
But then show the next slide.

00:20:57.290 --> 00:20:58.450
Just put this on.

00:20:58.450 --> 00:21:04.770
That's just one of
150 million responses

00:21:04.770 --> 00:21:07.430
you can get if you type in
control of your classroom.

00:21:07.430 --> 00:21:11.060
Teachers are obsessed,
obsessed, with keeping control.

00:21:11.060 --> 00:21:14.790
As matter of fact, they're--
and evaluated on the kind

00:21:14.790 --> 00:21:16.325
of control they
have in the class.

00:21:16.325 --> 00:21:17.950
So somebody comes in
the class and they

00:21:17.950 --> 00:21:21.320
expect everybody to be
sitting there quietly,

00:21:21.320 --> 00:21:25.250
quietly interacting with a
book or with a piece of paper

00:21:25.250 --> 00:21:28.540
and listening to the oracle
speak, the teacher, right?

00:21:28.540 --> 00:21:32.690
And so if you want to have
project-based learning

00:21:32.690 --> 00:21:34.930
and if you want to give
some students some control

00:21:34.930 --> 00:21:36.640
it looks very different.

00:21:36.640 --> 00:21:38.320
It looks messy.

00:21:38.320 --> 00:21:40.260
People are talking
to each other.

00:21:40.260 --> 00:21:44.470
Just like you saw those chairs
I have, they're all in groups.

00:21:44.470 --> 00:21:46.420
They're not all
lined up in a row.

00:21:46.420 --> 00:21:48.600
It's not all symmetrical.

00:21:48.600 --> 00:21:52.040
JAMIE CASAP: I would say that,
before The Media Center, when

00:21:52.040 --> 00:21:54.400
somebody would want
to go visit you,

00:21:54.400 --> 00:21:56.370
unlike a typical
classroom where you

00:21:56.370 --> 00:21:59.370
knew exactly where the teacher
was, it took like 15 minutes

00:21:59.370 --> 00:22:00.040
to find you.

00:22:00.040 --> 00:22:03.172
Because you're somewhere in the
back working with some team.

00:22:03.172 --> 00:22:04.630
Nobody could find
you at any point,

00:22:04.630 --> 00:22:07.754
because it looked
like it was chaotic.

00:22:07.754 --> 00:22:09.170
ESTHER WOJCICKI:
It looks chaotic.

00:22:09.170 --> 00:22:13.650
But you know, some people ask,
so how are these kids doing?

00:22:13.650 --> 00:22:17.310
Was their publication
good or how does it rank?

00:22:17.310 --> 00:22:20.100
So just so you know, we
have won consistently,

00:22:20.100 --> 00:22:23.240
for several years in a row,
the Gold Crown from Columbia.

00:22:23.240 --> 00:22:24.910
So it's the top of the nation.

00:22:24.910 --> 00:22:26.940
So it's not like
you're giving kids

00:22:26.940 --> 00:22:28.590
control and all
of a sudden, they

00:22:28.590 --> 00:22:30.620
start producing
low quality stuff.

00:22:30.620 --> 00:22:31.862
It's just the opposite.

00:22:31.862 --> 00:22:33.320
You give them some
control and then

00:22:33.320 --> 00:22:35.310
they feel passionate
about what they're doing

00:22:35.310 --> 00:22:37.340
and then they want
to make it the best.

00:22:37.340 --> 00:22:39.990
So I think that's really true.

00:22:39.990 --> 00:22:42.040
And finding me in the
classroom, that's right.

00:22:42.040 --> 00:22:43.900
It was hard to find
me in the classroom.

00:22:43.900 --> 00:22:46.830
So I was certified as
something called National Board

00:22:46.830 --> 00:22:49.350
Teacher, National Board
for Professional Teaching

00:22:49.350 --> 00:22:50.670
Standards.

00:22:50.670 --> 00:22:55.510
And they require you to
have a video of yourself.

00:22:55.510 --> 00:22:58.200
Here's another
problem, teaching.

00:22:58.200 --> 00:23:01.660
And so you have to
stand up and lecture

00:23:01.660 --> 00:23:04.560
and then they evaluate you.

00:23:04.560 --> 00:23:07.380
And then they either
certify you or don't.

00:23:07.380 --> 00:23:10.000
And that was the
biggest hangup for me.

00:23:10.000 --> 00:23:13.210
I had to organize
a special day when

00:23:13.210 --> 00:23:17.100
I could make them all sit
there and I could lecture

00:23:17.100 --> 00:23:18.392
and they could all sit quietly.

00:23:18.392 --> 00:23:20.391
JAMIE CASAP: You were
pretending like you were--

00:23:20.391 --> 00:23:21.830
ESTHER WOJCICKI:
I was pretending

00:23:21.830 --> 00:23:24.500
like this was my class.

00:23:24.500 --> 00:23:25.870
So you see, it's embedded.

00:23:25.870 --> 00:23:27.560
It's all over society.

00:23:27.560 --> 00:23:32.070
And so, if we can
somehow get this idea

00:23:32.070 --> 00:23:35.290
across that giving people
more freedom to learn,

00:23:35.290 --> 00:23:38.320
even if they're in bodies
that are younger than 18,

00:23:38.320 --> 00:23:40.581
will make a big difference
in their learning.

00:23:40.581 --> 00:23:42.330
JAMIE CASAP: I want
to ask you a question,

00:23:42.330 --> 00:23:46.490
and then as I do that, I want
to open it up for questions.

00:23:46.490 --> 00:23:48.200
So if you have
questions to ask Esther,

00:23:48.200 --> 00:23:49.450
there's a microphone up there.

00:23:49.450 --> 00:23:52.144
So think about your
questions as I ask you this.

00:23:52.144 --> 00:23:54.310
And then we'll have some
dialogue with the audience,

00:23:54.310 --> 00:23:55.640
because they're here.

00:23:55.640 --> 00:23:56.890
ESTHER WOJCICKI: That's great.

00:23:56.890 --> 00:23:58.222
That's great.

00:23:58.222 --> 00:24:00.180
JAMIE CASAP: If you're
talking to a new teacher

00:24:00.180 --> 00:24:01.810
or if you're talking
to a teacher who's

00:24:01.810 --> 00:24:03.684
been a teacher for five
years, doesn't really

00:24:03.684 --> 00:24:05.370
matter, what is the moonshot?

00:24:05.370 --> 00:24:07.105
What do you want
them to think about?

00:24:07.105 --> 00:24:08.730
You want them to read
your book and you

00:24:08.730 --> 00:24:10.781
want them to think about
very specific things

00:24:10.781 --> 00:24:12.280
that they can do
in their classroom.

00:24:12.280 --> 00:24:14.150
What's the big takeaway from it?

00:24:14.150 --> 00:24:17.574
ESTHER WOJCICKI: So the big
takeaway is like, for example,

00:24:17.574 --> 00:24:18.990
hopefully they'll
get Chromebooks.

00:24:18.990 --> 00:24:22.790
We just got Chrombooks
for the school.

00:24:22.790 --> 00:24:26.440
The first thing you want to
do is give them the Chromebook

00:24:26.440 --> 00:24:28.810
and teach them how to search.

00:24:28.810 --> 00:24:30.500
And search--
where's Dan Russell?

00:24:30.500 --> 00:24:31.000
He was--

00:24:31.000 --> 00:24:31.590
JAMIE CASAP: There he is.

00:24:31.590 --> 00:24:32.465
ESTHER WOJCICKI: Dan.

00:24:32.465 --> 00:24:32.980
Yes.

00:24:32.980 --> 00:24:37.480
Thank you, Dan, because this
is the first thing that they

00:24:37.480 --> 00:24:39.540
need to know how to do.

00:24:39.540 --> 00:24:42.690
And then after that, you
give them an assignment

00:24:42.690 --> 00:24:47.550
to do, for example, literally
anything, including math,

00:24:47.550 --> 00:24:50.480
you know, science.

00:24:50.480 --> 00:24:54.230
It's the entire curriculum
and you open it up.

00:24:54.230 --> 00:24:57.070
Instead of you lecturing,
like for example,

00:24:57.070 --> 00:24:59.740
even on Romeo and
Juliet, what's the story

00:24:59.740 --> 00:25:01.500
behind Romeo and Juliet?

00:25:01.500 --> 00:25:03.920
Well, how about
you guys go online,

00:25:03.920 --> 00:25:06.130
take a look at what
the resources are.

00:25:06.130 --> 00:25:08.500
What is the story
of Romeo and Juliet?

00:25:08.500 --> 00:25:10.690
You have 10 minutes
to find out and then

00:25:10.690 --> 00:25:12.960
I want you to talk to
each other in a group.

00:25:12.960 --> 00:25:13.950
What is the story?

00:25:13.950 --> 00:25:16.019
How did that come about?

00:25:16.019 --> 00:25:18.560
I'll tell you, they're going to
learn more in that 10 minutes

00:25:18.560 --> 00:25:21.640
than they would if I
spoke for 10 minutes

00:25:21.640 --> 00:25:23.310
and told them the story.

00:25:23.310 --> 00:25:25.800
They will not remember
anything I said.

00:25:25.800 --> 00:25:27.300
They're probably
dreaming about what

00:25:27.300 --> 00:25:30.030
they could do as soon as
they get out of school.

00:25:30.030 --> 00:25:33.480
So that's part of, I
think, what's going on

00:25:33.480 --> 00:25:35.070
and what they should be doing.

00:25:35.070 --> 00:25:38.590
And I think one of
the things that Google

00:25:38.590 --> 00:25:43.210
could do that would be helpful--
since all these publications I

00:25:43.210 --> 00:25:46.480
do, by the way, there
are all done on Docs.

00:25:46.480 --> 00:25:48.090
My hat off to the Docs team.

00:25:48.090 --> 00:25:51.350
I couldn't do any of this stuff
without the collaboration.

00:25:51.350 --> 00:25:54.960
They all peer edit everything.

00:25:54.960 --> 00:25:56.490
That's the way it works.

00:25:56.490 --> 00:25:59.350
And so one of the things
that would be great

00:25:59.350 --> 00:26:02.350
is if somehow we could
get that message across,

00:26:02.350 --> 00:26:05.960
that it's easier for
the teacher to teach

00:26:05.960 --> 00:26:09.200
and more effective for
the students to learn,

00:26:09.200 --> 00:26:12.400
if they would just
relinquish some control.

00:26:12.400 --> 00:26:14.740
And as I said, if the
blended learning model could

00:26:14.740 --> 00:26:17.600
be more effective
nationwide, we might not

00:26:17.600 --> 00:26:19.660
have that 40% dropout rate.

00:26:19.660 --> 00:26:22.342
You'd have more kids
that were engaged.

00:26:22.342 --> 00:26:23.300
JAMIE CASAP: Questions.

00:26:23.300 --> 00:26:24.200
What do we have?

00:26:24.200 --> 00:26:25.200
We have Esther here.

00:26:25.200 --> 00:26:28.084
Do we have some questions
from the audience?

00:26:28.084 --> 00:26:29.250
AUDIENCE: Thanks for coming.

00:26:29.250 --> 00:26:30.440
I've really enjoyed the talk.

00:26:30.440 --> 00:26:32.773
You mentioned that you believe
that the blended learning

00:26:32.773 --> 00:26:36.070
model can work in all
socioeconomic situations.

00:26:36.070 --> 00:26:39.130
Do you have any examples of
maybe where blended learning

00:26:39.130 --> 00:26:41.570
has been applied in the
lower socioeconomic kind

00:26:41.570 --> 00:26:45.220
of neighborhoods or demographic
and the success rates?

00:26:45.220 --> 00:26:46.880
ESTHER WOJCICKI:
You know, I don't

00:26:46.880 --> 00:26:50.060
have-- I didn't personally
teach in any of those areas.

00:26:50.060 --> 00:26:53.450
Although I can
say that last year

00:26:53.450 --> 00:26:57.960
I volunteered to teach the
lowest lane at Palo Alto High

00:26:57.960 --> 00:27:01.240
School, the majority of students
coming from East Palo Alto.

00:27:01.240 --> 00:27:03.750
And it worked with them too.

00:27:03.750 --> 00:27:07.870
And I was teaching
English in that program.

00:27:07.870 --> 00:27:09.660
JAMIE CASAP: I can
add, the methodology

00:27:09.660 --> 00:27:13.000
is being used by schools
all over the world, all

00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:14.310
over the country.

00:27:14.310 --> 00:27:17.230
There's a school in Philadelphia
called-- we could actually--

00:27:17.230 --> 00:27:19.360
there's a school here
in California, High Tech

00:27:19.360 --> 00:27:25.760
High, that uses project-based
learning and the zip codes

00:27:25.760 --> 00:27:28.550
that kids come from are all
over the place in Southern

00:27:28.550 --> 00:27:29.050
California.

00:27:29.050 --> 00:27:31.633
There's a school in Philadelphia
called the Science Leadership

00:27:31.633 --> 00:27:32.624
Academy, same thing.

00:27:32.624 --> 00:27:34.040
It's an inquiry-based
high school.

00:27:34.040 --> 00:27:36.165
It's all project-based
learning that they're doing.

00:27:36.165 --> 00:27:39.380
So the model applies even
more so, I think, sometimes

00:27:39.380 --> 00:27:42.550
in socioeconomic-- poorer
socioeconomic background

00:27:42.550 --> 00:27:46.030
schools because you're
putting kids together

00:27:46.030 --> 00:27:48.200
that have diverse backgrounds,
diverse perspectives

00:27:48.200 --> 00:27:50.490
and they're creating some
unusual and cool things.

00:27:50.490 --> 00:27:52.406
And so you're seeing a
lot of cool things come

00:27:52.406 --> 00:27:54.530
from that in those schools.

00:27:54.530 --> 00:27:57.530
ESTHER WOJCICKI: I think
it does work really well.

00:27:57.530 --> 00:28:00.910
Those kids are so used to being
told what to do all the time

00:28:00.910 --> 00:28:03.240
and being bossed around,
and so their idea

00:28:03.240 --> 00:28:07.580
of using tech in the classroom
is to have a worksheet online.

00:28:07.580 --> 00:28:10.702
And so you'll see kids
with those computers,

00:28:10.702 --> 00:28:12.660
and you think they're
doing something creative.

00:28:12.660 --> 00:28:13.579
Well, think again.

00:28:13.579 --> 00:28:14.120
They are not.

00:28:14.120 --> 00:28:17.350
They're just doing that same
thing, online worksheet.

00:28:17.350 --> 00:28:18.820
JAMIE CASAP: Let
me ask you about--

00:28:18.820 --> 00:28:21.017
did that answer your question?

00:28:21.017 --> 00:28:21.850
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:28:21.850 --> 00:28:24.391
JAMIE CASAP: So let me ask you
about professional development

00:28:24.391 --> 00:28:25.220
for teachers.

00:28:25.220 --> 00:28:28.185
What do you like about
professional development?

00:28:28.185 --> 00:28:30.310
I almost didn't
want to ask that.

00:28:30.310 --> 00:28:33.519
What would you change about
professional development

00:28:33.519 --> 00:28:34.060
for teachers?

00:28:34.060 --> 00:28:37.625
What's wrong in
that set up system?

00:28:37.625 --> 00:28:39.000
ESTHER WOJCICKI:
Is there anybody

00:28:39.000 --> 00:28:42.090
in here who has been a teacher?

00:28:42.090 --> 00:28:44.180
So you remember what
professional development

00:28:44.180 --> 00:28:45.130
is like?

00:28:45.130 --> 00:28:47.560
So they bring in
some high paid guy

00:28:47.560 --> 00:28:50.915
to speak to you at the
beginning of whatever day

00:28:50.915 --> 00:28:52.460
it is, and they speak.

00:28:52.460 --> 00:28:54.940
It's a lecture-based model.

00:28:54.940 --> 00:28:57.064
And then they ask you
afterward to get together

00:28:57.064 --> 00:28:59.480
in little groups and tell you
what you thought of that guy

00:28:59.480 --> 00:29:01.100
that's spoke.

00:29:01.100 --> 00:29:03.230
I would change that whole thing.

00:29:03.230 --> 00:29:05.600
I mean, I would
have people actually

00:29:05.600 --> 00:29:09.300
doing exactly what we
recommend in the classroom.

00:29:09.300 --> 00:29:11.170
Teachers should
do the same thing,

00:29:11.170 --> 00:29:12.600
put themselves
together in groups,

00:29:12.600 --> 00:29:14.490
talk about issues
in their classroom,

00:29:14.490 --> 00:29:18.290
find solutions, and then share.

00:29:18.290 --> 00:29:20.610
It's kind of like the
unconference model.

00:29:20.610 --> 00:29:23.700
You know the
unconference, like--

00:29:23.700 --> 00:29:26.200
JAMIE CASAP: The unconference
model where it's self-driven

00:29:26.200 --> 00:29:27.611
and the participants
are actually

00:29:27.611 --> 00:29:29.985
driving the conversation, as
opposed to being lectured to

00:29:29.985 --> 00:29:31.320
by someone who comes in.

00:29:31.320 --> 00:29:32.830
ESTHER WOJCICKI:
That's right, yeah.

00:29:32.830 --> 00:29:36.380
I mean I think lecture-based
works to a certain extent.

00:29:36.380 --> 00:29:39.870
That's why I said, the
blended learning, 50%.

00:29:39.870 --> 00:29:42.070
OK you come lecture for 50%.

00:29:42.070 --> 00:29:45.510
But then after that,
you need to stop.

00:29:45.510 --> 00:29:46.160
Cut it out.

00:29:46.160 --> 00:29:48.080
JAMIE CASAP: What
skills do teachers

00:29:48.080 --> 00:29:52.900
need to be able to implement
this model that they don't

00:29:52.900 --> 00:29:55.995
necessarily have now or they're
not necessarily utilizing now?

00:29:55.995 --> 00:29:57.620
ESTHER WOJCICKI: I
think the main thing

00:29:57.620 --> 00:30:03.510
is they have to let go of
their fear of giving students

00:30:03.510 --> 00:30:05.310
some control.

00:30:05.310 --> 00:30:07.690
I mean, it looks
messy, it really does.

00:30:07.690 --> 00:30:09.240
Kids will be talking
to each other.

00:30:09.240 --> 00:30:13.240
They might not turn
their stuff in on time.

00:30:13.240 --> 00:30:16.900
But after a short
period of that,

00:30:16.900 --> 00:30:19.520
you're still collecting work.

00:30:19.520 --> 00:30:23.000
You know, I collect
all the stuff online.

00:30:23.000 --> 00:30:25.020
And then all corrected online.

00:30:25.020 --> 00:30:28.010
But if you want, you can
collected in hard copy,

00:30:28.010 --> 00:30:29.790
or you can get other
kids-- you know,

00:30:29.790 --> 00:30:31.470
you're still doing
the same thing.

00:30:31.470 --> 00:30:32.980
The only difference
is that you're

00:30:32.980 --> 00:30:35.090
giving them more control.

00:30:35.090 --> 00:30:37.130
You're not dictating
to such a degree.

00:30:39.730 --> 00:30:44.370
And I think that as I mentioned,
the main thing that teachers

00:30:44.370 --> 00:30:46.800
are afraid of is losing
control, because that's

00:30:46.800 --> 00:30:49.630
what you're trained to do
in a school of education.

00:30:49.630 --> 00:30:52.050
And that's what your
principal comes through.

00:30:52.050 --> 00:30:54.640
They have this thing
called scripted teaching.

00:30:54.640 --> 00:30:56.790
Are you familiar with
scripted teaching?

00:30:56.790 --> 00:30:58.080
Anyone know about it?

00:30:58.080 --> 00:31:01.230
It's right here in
Santa Clara County.

00:31:01.230 --> 00:31:05.820
Scripted teaching is basically,
they give you a textbook.

00:31:05.820 --> 00:31:07.610
They give you
exactly what you're

00:31:07.610 --> 00:31:09.560
supposed to say
and tell you where

00:31:09.560 --> 00:31:13.360
you're supposed to be on every
single day of the school year.

00:31:13.360 --> 00:31:14.800
And they give you the tests too.

00:31:14.800 --> 00:31:20.190
It's happening right now,
right here, as we speak.

00:31:20.190 --> 00:31:23.230
And the question is,
how effective is that?

00:31:23.230 --> 00:31:26.640
And I would say, it's
not very effective.

00:31:26.640 --> 00:31:31.900
Doesn't seem-- we have
600,000 jobs that go unfilled.

00:31:31.900 --> 00:31:32.880
Did you know that?

00:31:32.880 --> 00:31:33.440
JAMIE CASAP: Uh, huh.

00:31:33.440 --> 00:31:35.439
ESTHER WOJCICKI: And the
reason they go unfilled

00:31:35.439 --> 00:31:38.200
is because they can't find
people with the right skills

00:31:38.200 --> 00:31:40.010
to fill those jobs.

00:31:40.010 --> 00:31:42.780
We're training for
a factory model.

00:31:42.780 --> 00:31:48.420
And of course, as I mentioned,
in schools like in Oakland,

00:31:48.420 --> 00:31:50.220
Oakland's dropout rate is 70%.

00:31:53.310 --> 00:31:54.350
Did you guys know that?

00:31:54.350 --> 00:31:57.780
Isn't that something
scary, I think?

00:31:57.780 --> 00:32:01.350
San Jose actually has a pretty
high dropout rate as well.

00:32:01.350 --> 00:32:03.930
JAMIE CASAP: So we had some
people lining up for questions.

00:32:03.930 --> 00:32:06.560
And I have some others,
but I'll start up here.

00:32:09.110 --> 00:32:11.640
AUDIENCE: So could you
talk a little about blended

00:32:11.640 --> 00:32:13.990
learning for younger age groups?

00:32:13.990 --> 00:32:15.490
ESTHER WOJCICKI:
That's a good idea.

00:32:15.490 --> 00:32:16.010
JAMIE CASAP: That's
a good question.

00:32:16.010 --> 00:32:16.926
ESTHER WOJCICKI: Yeah.

00:32:16.926 --> 00:32:22.010
So you know, even little kids,
small kids, preschool kids,

00:32:22.010 --> 00:32:25.180
even they like to work
together with their friends.

00:32:25.180 --> 00:32:28.375
They're all coming to
school to see their friends.

00:32:28.375 --> 00:32:31.000
If anybody's a teacher in here,
I don't want to disappoint you.

00:32:31.000 --> 00:32:34.180
They're not coming to see you.

00:32:34.180 --> 00:32:38.240
And the same thing happens
in elementary school.

00:32:38.240 --> 00:32:40.880
So you want to give
kids an opportunity

00:32:40.880 --> 00:32:42.720
to work in a peer group.

00:32:42.720 --> 00:32:44.120
You can be more directive.

00:32:44.120 --> 00:32:48.045
That's why I say even 50%,
but you can do the same thing.

00:32:50.630 --> 00:32:52.390
Kids get excited about that.

00:32:52.390 --> 00:32:55.140
It works in elementary
school as well.

00:32:55.140 --> 00:32:57.040
There are some
subjects where I think

00:32:57.040 --> 00:33:01.100
it's a little bit harder to
do it than in other subjects,

00:33:01.100 --> 00:33:05.280
like for example, perhaps
science, chemistry.

00:33:05.280 --> 00:33:08.910
Chemistry is so much
memorization and so forth.

00:33:08.910 --> 00:33:13.420
