years, something like that.

00:45:10.690 --> 00:45:12.560
But it's just to give
them some perspective.

00:45:12.560 --> 00:45:14.940
You don't have to go to Harvard.

00:45:14.940 --> 00:45:16.660
You know you can go
to Foothill College.

00:45:16.660 --> 00:45:18.820
You can go to any
school or you don't even

00:45:18.820 --> 00:45:21.940
have to go to school maybe, if
you want to do something else.

00:45:21.940 --> 00:45:23.940
You need to think about
what you want to do.

00:45:23.940 --> 00:45:26.480
So more teachers
have to say that.

00:45:26.480 --> 00:45:28.820
Because they don't
listen to their parents

00:45:28.820 --> 00:45:30.200
when they're teenagers.

00:45:30.200 --> 00:45:32.200
Sorry to shock you.

00:45:32.200 --> 00:45:33.394
But anyway--

00:45:33.394 --> 00:45:35.310
JAMIE CASAP: But it's
all part of this whole--

00:45:35.310 --> 00:45:37.268
we talked a little bit
about earlier, this idea

00:45:37.268 --> 00:45:39.750
that it's an individual sport.

00:45:39.750 --> 00:45:42.740
And not only that, we make them
compete against each other,

00:45:42.740 --> 00:45:43.240
right?

00:45:43.240 --> 00:45:46.240
So they are competing
for grades and sometimes

00:45:46.240 --> 00:45:48.830
instead of figuring out how to
collaborate, they're competing

00:45:48.830 --> 00:45:50.012
and that causes issues.

00:45:50.012 --> 00:45:51.470
ESTHER WOJCICKI:
That causes issues

00:45:51.470 --> 00:45:55.200
and especially if teacher
grades on a curve,

00:45:55.200 --> 00:45:58.070
you're just grading
on an absolute scale,

00:45:58.070 --> 00:46:00.790
and certain number kids get
an A and then another B,

00:46:00.790 --> 00:46:02.970
and then they talk
about grade inflation.

00:46:02.970 --> 00:46:04.710
And then kids are
checking their phone.

00:46:04.710 --> 00:46:05.376
I'm not kidding.

00:46:05.376 --> 00:46:09.120
They check their phone
every 20 minutes.

00:46:09.120 --> 00:46:10.145
I don't post grades.

00:46:10.145 --> 00:46:11.330
It's like, finished.

00:46:11.330 --> 00:46:12.440
Sorry, guys.

00:46:12.440 --> 00:46:15.990
Just learn and then when you're
done doing that learning,

00:46:15.990 --> 00:46:19.620
you can get an A and
then they're actually

00:46:19.620 --> 00:46:22.100
very happy about this,
to be honest, no stress.

00:46:22.100 --> 00:46:23.600
JAMIE CASAP: It's
constant iteration

00:46:23.600 --> 00:46:28.030
versus having some absolute time
where you get a B, like what

00:46:28.030 --> 00:46:29.090
does a B mean, right?

00:46:29.090 --> 00:46:32.010
What do you do with a B
versus continuously learning

00:46:32.010 --> 00:46:32.572
to iterate.

00:46:32.572 --> 00:46:34.530
ESTHER WOJCICKI: I think
more and more programs

00:46:34.530 --> 00:46:35.760
need to be like that.

00:46:35.760 --> 00:46:40.230
And I think that Gunn
High School could benefit.

00:46:40.230 --> 00:46:42.360
JAMIE CASAP: Well, most
high schools can benefit.

00:46:42.360 --> 00:46:43.860
ESTHER WOJCICKI:
Right, most schools

00:46:43.860 --> 00:46:45.080
can benefit, not just Gunn.

00:46:45.080 --> 00:46:46.580
AUDIENCE: First, I
want to thank you

00:46:46.580 --> 00:46:49.900
for what you were just saying
about stress on the kids.

00:46:49.900 --> 00:46:52.830
I have teenagers applying
to college right now.

00:46:52.830 --> 00:46:56.680
But my question is
actually about how do you

00:46:56.680 --> 00:46:59.990
apply some of this in a state
like my home state of New

00:46:59.990 --> 00:47:02.970
Mexico, where the
poverty is so great,

00:47:02.970 --> 00:47:05.555
the biggest barrier to learning
a lot of these kids face

00:47:05.555 --> 00:47:06.770
is just basic hunger.

00:47:06.770 --> 00:47:08.512
The teachers are
bringing in food

00:47:08.512 --> 00:47:10.970
to feed the students so they
can learn, that kind of stuff.

00:47:10.970 --> 00:47:13.659
How do you apply the
project-based learning

00:47:13.659 --> 00:47:15.950
to a school that can't afford
any technology whatsoever

00:47:15.950 --> 00:47:18.899
and can't even afford
to get the heat working?

00:47:18.899 --> 00:47:20.440
JAMIE CASAP: That's
a great question.

00:47:20.440 --> 00:47:21.400
ESTHER WOJCICKI: That's
a great question.

00:47:21.400 --> 00:47:21.890
JAMIE CASAP: You take it.

00:47:21.890 --> 00:47:22.734
I'm not taking it.

00:47:26.350 --> 00:47:27.686
This is your show, not mine.

00:47:32.670 --> 00:47:35.190
ESTHER WOJCICKI: My
very first teaching job,

00:47:35.190 --> 00:47:39.850
I had a class full of boys
period one in the morning.

00:47:39.850 --> 00:47:43.600
And that was their number one
problem, they were hungry.

00:47:43.600 --> 00:47:49.800
And I was in San Leandro and,
you know, it's a major problem.

00:47:49.800 --> 00:47:53.000
It's too bad that the-- you
know, somebody in the community

00:47:53.000 --> 00:47:54.120
has to solve the problem.

00:47:54.120 --> 00:47:57.000
I solved the problem by
bringing in food every day.

00:47:57.000 --> 00:47:59.690
And then the
administration wanted

00:47:59.690 --> 00:48:02.770
to know what I had done
to make these boys learn.

00:48:02.770 --> 00:48:08.340
And it was just so simple,
just food in the morning.

00:48:08.340 --> 00:48:13.360
So it's very hard to
learn when you're hungry.

00:48:13.360 --> 00:48:15.950
And it's also hard to learn
when you don't have a place

00:48:15.950 --> 00:48:17.110
to live or stay.

00:48:17.110 --> 00:48:20.490
We have a lot of
homeless kids in America.

00:48:20.490 --> 00:48:22.732
JAMIE CASAP: Let's make
that we're clear here,

00:48:22.732 --> 00:48:24.690
that blended learning or
project-based learning

00:48:24.690 --> 00:48:27.460
is one component of a
giant scope of things

00:48:27.460 --> 00:48:30.770
that we have to do in education
in terms of a learning model.

00:48:30.770 --> 00:48:32.530
But you asked a
great question, which

00:48:32.530 --> 00:48:36.160
I'll kind of create more
of a general question

00:48:36.160 --> 00:48:39.830
around this, which is the use
of technology in education,

00:48:39.830 --> 00:48:42.660
we're seeing an increase of the
use of technology in education.

00:48:42.660 --> 00:48:45.850
Some schools can afford it,
some schools can't afford it.

00:48:45.850 --> 00:48:49.630
But more importantly, you did
not take technology and just

00:48:49.630 --> 00:48:54.070
put it on top of old
learning models and do that.

00:48:54.070 --> 00:48:57.920
You actually embedded and
integrated the technology

00:48:57.920 --> 00:48:58.680
in education.

00:48:58.680 --> 00:49:01.760
So a lot of times, we see
technology as this nice

00:49:01.760 --> 00:49:05.400
to have, because we're adding it
on top of things, versus being

00:49:05.400 --> 00:49:09.430
a core enabling capability
to new learning models that

00:49:09.430 --> 00:49:12.010
get you to that motivation
that you want from kids.

00:49:12.010 --> 00:49:14.680
So talk about the role of
technology in education

00:49:14.680 --> 00:49:18.510
then what you're seeing
good and also bad.

00:49:18.510 --> 00:49:21.770
ESTHER WOJCICKI: So good is
when it's embedded in a way

00:49:21.770 --> 00:49:24.890
that it supports the learning.

00:49:24.890 --> 00:49:28.600
It's bad when it just continues
to reinforce worksheets.

00:49:28.600 --> 00:49:33.380
And when kids are
just put on a computer

00:49:33.380 --> 00:49:37.640
nonstop for, I'm not kidding,
long periods of time,

00:49:37.640 --> 00:49:39.024
it can be for hours.

00:49:39.024 --> 00:49:40.190
JAMIE CASAP: Drill and kill.

00:49:40.190 --> 00:49:41.523
ESTHER WOJCICKI: Drill and kill.

00:49:41.523 --> 00:49:42.769
That is not a good model.

00:49:42.769 --> 00:49:44.810
And I don't know if you
know, but in Florida they

00:49:44.810 --> 00:49:48.410
have had some problems
with the tech-based schools

00:49:48.410 --> 00:49:51.530
because the kids were just
put on the computer all day,

00:49:51.530 --> 00:49:53.500
and then they didn't
learn anything.

00:49:53.500 --> 00:49:55.780
And that's one of the
other problems with MOOCs.

00:49:55.780 --> 00:49:59.980
You know MOOCs, massive
open online courses?

00:49:59.980 --> 00:50:02.560
People don't like
to learn alone.

00:50:02.560 --> 00:50:03.970
Nobody wants to learn alone.

00:50:03.970 --> 00:50:07.550
Their dropout rate is 95%.

00:50:07.550 --> 00:50:11.160
So if you put it in a
classroom where then kids

00:50:11.160 --> 00:50:14.210
are talking and interacting
with each other,

00:50:14.210 --> 00:50:15.680
then they want to stay.

00:50:15.680 --> 00:50:18.710
So my question on
those is, can you do it

00:50:18.710 --> 00:50:22.856
online as opposed to in person?

00:50:22.856 --> 00:50:24.480
JAMIE CASAP: The key
message is that we

00:50:24.480 --> 00:50:27.630
have to figure out ways to
take technology and support

00:50:27.630 --> 00:50:29.765
and enable these great
learning models that

00:50:29.765 --> 00:50:31.932
are being created that you
champion and are part of.

00:50:31.932 --> 00:50:33.473
ESTHER WOJCICKI:
That's what teachers

00:50:33.473 --> 00:50:36.110
need to learn in their
professional development, how

00:50:36.110 --> 00:50:41.100
to take technology and use it
to support their teaching, not

00:50:41.100 --> 00:50:48.870
in place and just to make a huge
difference to get kids excited.

00:50:48.870 --> 00:50:54.239
I think it needs-- it makes a
huge difference for America.

00:50:54.239 --> 00:50:56.030
JAMIE CASAP: We've got
two more folks here.

00:50:56.030 --> 00:50:57.750
Let's make sure-- I want to
get everybody's questions

00:50:57.750 --> 00:50:58.740
in before we run out of time.

00:50:58.740 --> 00:51:00.114
So come up and
ask your question.

00:51:00.114 --> 00:51:02.770
AUDIENCE: Quickly, I'm
curious about your experience

00:51:02.770 --> 00:51:06.310
with how much guidance to
give the groups of kids

00:51:06.310 --> 00:51:10.650
when they break out into their
own independent assignments.

00:51:10.650 --> 00:51:13.270
Do you just give
them a task and let

00:51:13.270 --> 00:51:15.820
them completely
self-organize or do

00:51:15.820 --> 00:51:19.030
you come in after a few
minutes and give some guidance?

00:51:19.030 --> 00:51:21.540
I know from my team
working at Google,

00:51:21.540 --> 00:51:24.850
many times we're challenged
on how to collaborate together

00:51:24.850 --> 00:51:26.940
with our peers.

00:51:26.940 --> 00:51:28.850
ESTHER WOJCICKI:
That's a good question.

00:51:28.850 --> 00:51:33.380
So what I do, first, I just let
them pick their own partners,

00:51:33.380 --> 00:51:33.950
by the way.

00:51:33.950 --> 00:51:36.970
Some teachers tell
you who to be with you

00:51:36.970 --> 00:51:39.040
and then they don't
want to do that.

00:51:39.040 --> 00:51:43.750
So you pick your partners
and you have your project.

00:51:43.750 --> 00:51:46.080
And then I come around
usually, and I'm like,

00:51:46.080 --> 00:51:48.530
so what did you
guys decide to do?

00:51:48.530 --> 00:51:52.450
And can you explain to me
why is this a good idea?

00:51:52.450 --> 00:51:56.410
I don't just leave them in
the infrastructure is there.

00:51:56.410 --> 00:52:00.820
It's just that I give
them more responsibility.

00:52:00.820 --> 00:52:03.720
JAMIE CASAP: And you let them
make decisions as well, right?

00:52:03.720 --> 00:52:05.290
You and I have
talked about, there's

00:52:05.290 --> 00:52:08.220
been controversial articles
that the students wanted

00:52:08.220 --> 00:52:10.170
to write about and
you guide them,

00:52:10.170 --> 00:52:13.030
but you don't tell
them what to do

00:52:13.030 --> 00:52:14.620
or how to position something.

00:52:14.620 --> 00:52:16.280
You give them the
framework to do that.

00:52:16.280 --> 00:52:17.380
ESTHER WOJCICKI: 100%.

00:52:17.380 --> 00:52:20.280
If they'd be here, they
would tell you themselves

00:52:20.280 --> 00:52:23.800
that they feel so
empowered that they tell me

00:52:23.800 --> 00:52:26.846
they are in charge of the
whole class, everything.

00:52:26.846 --> 00:52:27.970
Because they feel that way.

00:52:27.970 --> 00:52:30.640
But in fact, I meet
with them all the time

00:52:30.640 --> 00:52:32.350
and give them suggestions.

00:52:32.350 --> 00:52:35.920
So every day after school or
maybe at lunchtime or something

00:52:35.920 --> 00:52:37.170
like that, email.

00:52:39.730 --> 00:52:43.220
But I'm not the parent, see,
so they're not threatened by--

00:52:43.220 --> 00:52:45.830
and also I make
them as suggestions.

00:52:45.830 --> 00:52:48.420
I don't say you have to do this.

00:52:48.420 --> 00:52:51.040
I mean that is really the key.

00:52:51.040 --> 00:52:53.490
And so with groups
here at Google,

00:52:53.490 --> 00:52:55.680
I would go around and
talk to them often.

00:52:55.680 --> 00:52:59.679
I mean one thing that's great
about Google, great people.

00:52:59.679 --> 00:53:01.970
I mean I don't think I've
met a single person at Google

00:53:01.970 --> 00:53:03.250
that I wasn't impressed with.

00:53:03.250 --> 00:53:07.040
You guys are all amazing.

00:53:07.040 --> 00:53:08.830
So I'm sure that--

00:53:08.830 --> 00:53:10.570
JAMIE CASAP: We're doing OK?

00:53:10.570 --> 00:53:13.346
ESTHER WOJCICKI: Yeah, you seem
to be doing just fantastically.

